                <!-- Slide 1: Investigative Planning -->
                <div class="slide" data-slide-num="1">
                    <h2>Investigative Planning & Legal Considerations</h2>
                    
                    <h3>Why Proper Investigation Techniques Matter</h3>
                    
                    <div class="concept-card burgundy">
                        <h4>Public Protection</h4>
                        <p>Investigations address potential harm and prevent future violations.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="concept-card gold">
                        <h4>Legal Defensibility</h4>
                        <p>Properly conducted investigations withstand legal scrutiny.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="concept-card blue">
                        <h4>Fairness</h4>
                        <p>Thorough investigations protect both the public and the rights of licensees.</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="concept-card gray">
                        <h4>Accountability</h4>
                        <p>Investigations demonstrate regulatory bodies take complaints seriously.</p>
                    </div>

                    <h3>Prior Planning Prevents Poor Performance</h3>
                    <p>Preparing an investigation plan and following it ensures investigators conduct thorough, legally defensible investigations. Planning prevents missed evidence, legal missteps, and incomplete findings. It's your roadmap from complaint to conclusion.</p>

                    <h3>What is an Investigative Plan?</h3>
                    <p>An investigation plan answers the fundamental questions about what happened and outlines how you'll gather the evidence to answer those questions. It's both a planning tool and an organizational framework for your investigation.</p>
                    
                    <p>Think of it as a roadmap that guides your investigation while remaining flexible enough to adapt to new information and unexpected developments.</p>

                    <h3>The Six Fundamental Questions</h3>
                    <p>Every investigation must answer six basic questions. These questions form the foundation of your investigation plan:</p>

                    <div class="concept-card blue" style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0;">
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong>üë§ WHO?</strong><br>Complainant, victim, respondent, witnesses</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong>üìù WHAT?</strong><br>Alleged violation, evidence needed</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong>üìÖ WHEN?</strong><br>Timeframe of violation</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong>üìç WHERE?</strong><br>Location of violation, parties, evidence</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong>ü§î WHY?</strong><br>Root cause analysis</li>
                            <li style="margin-bottom: 15px;"><strong>‚öôÔ∏è HOW?</strong><br>Mechanism of violation</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <h3>Additional Planning Considerations</h3>
                    
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0;">
                        <div class="concept-card gold">
                            <h4>üõ†Ô∏è Tools & Equipment</h4>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Cameras for documentation</li>
                                <li>Evidence collection gear</li>
                                <li>Audio recorders</li>
                                <li>Personal protective equipment</li>
                                <li>Vehicles for travel</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>

                        <div class="concept-card burgundy">
                            <h4>üí∞ Budget Considerations</h4>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Travel expenses</li>
                                <li>Expert witness fees</li>
                                <li>Undercover purchases</li>
                                <li>Equipment rental</li>
                                <li>Document retrieval costs</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="highlight-box">
                        <h4>üí° Planning Principle</h4>
                        <p>Time spent planning is never wasted. A thorough investigation plan prevents missed evidence, reduces the need for follow-up, and ensures your investigation will withstand scrutiny.</p>
                    </div>

                    <h3>Legal Considerations</h3>
                    <p>While many regulatory agencies require cooperation with investigations, individuals and businesses typically have legal protections against government intrusion. Understanding these protections, and your jurisdiction's specific requirements, is essential for conducting legally defensible investigations.</p>

                    <p><strong>Click each card below to learn about the legal considerations impacting investigations:</strong></p>

                    <div class="gallery-grid">
                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(1, 1)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üìú Protection Against Unreasonable Searches</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p>Most jurisdictions provide constitutional or statutory protections against unreasonable government searches and seizures. For example, in the United States, the 4th Amendment states:</p>
                                <p style="font-style: italic; margin: 15px 0;">"The right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures, shall not be violated..."</p>
                                <h4>What this means for investigators:</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Warrants or proper authorization may be required for searches, even in regulatory contexts</li>
                                    <li>Warrants must typically be based on probable cause or reasonable grounds</li>
                                    <li>Warrants must specifically describe what will be searched and seized</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Important</h4>
                                <p>Similar protections exist in Canada (Charter of Rights and Freedoms), Australia, and other jurisdictions. Always consult your jurisdiction's specific requirements.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(1, 2)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">‚öñÔ∏è Due Process Protections</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p>Regulatory investigations must respect due process rights, which exist in various forms across jurisdictions. These typically include:</p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Notice:</strong> Informing parties they're under investigation (timing varies by jurisdiction)</li>
                                    <li><strong>Opportunity to respond:</strong> Allowing parties to present their side</li>
                                    <li><strong>Fair procedures:</strong> Following established investigative procedures</li>
                                    <li><strong>Right to counsel:</strong> Allowing legal representation in many circumstances</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Critical Point</h4>
                                <p>Sub-national governments (states, provinces, territories) often must apply the same or stronger protections as their national government. Check your specific jurisdictional requirements.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(1, 3)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üìã Relevant Legal Precedents</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p>Court decisions in many jurisdictions have established that regulatory authority doesn't eliminate legal protections. In the United States, for example:</p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Camara v. Municipal Court:</strong> Established warrant requirement for administrative inspections</li>
                                    <li><strong>See v. City of Seattle:</strong> Extended warrant requirement to commercial properties</li>
                                    <li><strong>Marshall v. Barlow's Inc.:</strong> OSHA inspections require warrants if business demands one</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Universal Principle</h4>
                                <p>When a business or individual demands proper authorization, regulators must obtain it. Similar principles apply across many jurisdictions, consult your local legal requirements.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(1, 4)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üìÑ Administrative Subpoenas / Summons</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p><strong>What they are:</strong> Legal orders issued by agencies to compel a person or business to provide documents or testimony. (Terminology varies: "subpoena" in US, "summons" in some other jurisdictions).</p>
                                <h4>General Requirements</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Agency must have statutory authority to issue compulsory orders</li>
                                    <li>The order must be relevant to the investigation</li>
                                    <li>The order must not be overly broad</li>
                                    <li>Recipients typically can challenge the order</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Important</h4>
                                <p>Check your agency's specific authority and procedural requirements for issuing compulsory process.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="scenario-box" style="margin-top: 30px;">
                        <h3>Scenario:</h3>
                        <p>You're investigating a complaint that a licensed dental practice is reusing single-use equipment.</p>
                        <p>When you arrive at the office to conduct an inspection, the office manager asks to see your warrant or proper authorization.</p>
                        <p>The practice has never been inspected before, and you have no authorization document with you.</p>
                        <h3 style="color: #64092c;">What should you do?</h3>
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Think about:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Do you need a warrant for regulatory inspections in your jurisdiction?</li>
                            <li>Can you proceed without consent if the business demands authorization?</li>
                            <li>What are the consequences of proceeding without proper authorization?</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 15px; background: #fff9e6; border-radius: 6px;"><strong>üí° Key Insight:</strong> When authorization is demanded, you typically must obtain it before proceeding, even in highly regulated industries. Proceeding without authorization when demanded could result in evidence being excluded or the investigation being challenged.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Slide 2: Information Sources -->
                <div class="slide" data-slide-num="2">
                    <h2>Information Sources</h2>
                    
                    <p>A thorough investigation draws from multiple sources of information. Each source provides a different perspective and different types of evidence. Understanding these sources helps you plan comprehensive investigations.</p>

                    <p><strong>Click each card below to learn about the seven basic sources of investigative information:</strong></p>

                    <div class="gallery-grid">
                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(2, 1)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üì¢ The Complainant</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p><strong>Role in the investigation:</strong> The complainant provides the foundation of your investigation, the initial allegation and complaint that triggers the investigative process.</p>
                                <h4>What they provide:</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>The allegation itself (what they claim happened)</li>
                                    <li>Their account of events and timeline</li>
                                    <li>Identification of potential witnesses</li>
                                    <li>Leads to documentation and evidence</li>
                                    <li>Context about the situation</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Important considerations</h4>
                                <p>The complainant's perspective is just one side of the story. Verify their claims through independent evidence and other sources. Document their complaint thoroughly, including dates, times, specific allegations, and any supporting documentation they provide.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(2, 2)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üîç The Investigator</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p><strong>Why investigators are a source:</strong> Investigators have access to institutional knowledge, previous investigations, case files, and other investigators' experiences that provide crucial context.</p>
                                <h4>What investigators provide:</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Previous investigations:</strong> Has this respondent been investigated before? Are there patterns?</li>
                                    <li><strong>Institutional knowledge:</strong> Understanding of common issues in this profession or industry</li>
                                    <li><strong>Investigation files:</strong> Comprehensive documentation from past cases</li>
                                    <li><strong>Colleague experience:</strong> Other investigators who've handled similar cases</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p><strong>Best practice:</strong> Review previous investigation files early in your planning. They often reveal patterns, identify recurring witnesses, and suggest effective investigation strategies.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(2, 3)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üëî The Respondent</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p><strong>Role in the investigation:</strong> The respondent is the person or business against whom the complaint has been made. They provide their version of events and their documentary evidence.</p>
                                <h4>What they provide:</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Their account of what happened</li>
                                    <li>Documentation supporting their position</li>
                                    <li>Identification of witnesses favorable to their case</li>
                                    <li>Alternative explanations for events</li>
                                    <li>Context about policies, procedures, and circumstances</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Important note</h4>
                                <p>The respondent has a vested interest in the outcome. While their perspective must be heard and documented, verify their claims independently. Fair investigations require hearing both sides while objectively evaluating all evidence.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(2, 4)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üë• Witnesses</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p><strong>Role in the investigation:</strong> Witnesses provide third-party accounts of events, adding credibility and independent verification to either party's claims.</p>
                                <h4>What they provide:</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Independent accounts of what happened</li>
                                    <li>Corroboration (or contradiction) of party statements</li>
                                    <li>Additional context and details</li>
                                    <li>Identification of other witnesses or evidence locations</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Critical consideration</h4>
                                <p>Always assess witness relationships with the complainant or respondent. A witness who is the respondent's business partner has different potential biases than a neutral third party. Document these relationships and consider them when weighing witness credibility.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(2, 5)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üìÅ Public Records</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p><strong>What they are:</strong> Records accessible to everyone, either in hard copy or through the internet, maintained by government agencies and public entities.</p>
                                <h4>Types of public records:</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Court records (civil, criminal, family court)</li>
                                    <li>Business and professional licenses</li>
                                    <li>Marriage and divorce records</li>
                                    <li>Property ownership and transfer records</li>
                                    <li>DMV records (may require legal process)</li>
                                    <li>Public contracts and bids</li>
                                    <li>Other government agency records</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Value in investigations</h4>
                                <p>Public records provide objective, independently verified information. They're particularly useful for establishing timelines, verifying claims, and discovering connections between parties.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(2, 6)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üîí Private Records</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p><strong>What they are:</strong> Documents and records held by private entities that are not generally available to the public.</p>
                                <h4>Types of private records:</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Medical records (HIPAA protected)</li>
                                    <li>Security camera footage</li>
                                    <li>Personnel files</li>
                                    <li>Private contracts and agreements</li>
                                    <li>Company policies and procedures</li>
                                    <li>Financial records</li>
                                    <li>Email and internal communications</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>How to obtain them</h4>
                                <p>Private records may be obtained voluntarily from parties cooperating with your investigation. When cooperation isn't forthcoming, you may need compulsory process such as an administrative subpoena or, in some cases, a search warrant.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="gallery-card" onclick="revealGallery(2, 7)">
                            <div class="gallery-card-title">üî¨ Physical & Electronic Evidence</div>
                            <div class="gallery-card-content">
                                <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Tangible items and digital data that investigators physically collect as part of their investigation.</p>
                                <h4>Types of physical and electronic evidence:</h4>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Scientific evidence (lab samples, drug testing results)</li>
                                    <li>Surveillance footage collected during investigation</li>
                                    <li>DNA or fingerprint evidence</li>
                                    <li>Hard drives, external drives, USB devices</li>
                                    <li>Physical items (equipment, documents, products)</li>
                                    <li>Photographs and video documentation</li>
                                    <li>Audio recordings</li>
                                </ul>
                                <h4>Critical requirement</h4>
                                <p>Maintain proper chain of custody for all physical and electronic evidence. Document who collected it, when, where, how it was stored, and who accessed it. This documentation is essential if evidence is challenged.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <h4>üí° Investigation Principle</h4>
                        <p>The most thorough investigations draw from multiple sources. No single source tells the complete story. Cross-reference information from different sources to build a complete, accurate picture of what happened.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Slide 3: Executing Your Plan -->
                <div class="slide" data-slide-num="3">
                    <h2>Executing Your Plan</h2>
                    
                    <p>Once your investigation plan is complete, execution is largely about following your roadmap. However, just like any journey, you must remain flexible when unexpected issues arise.</p>

                    <h3>üó∫Ô∏è Following the Roadmap</h3>
                    <div class="concept-card blue">
                        <p>Your investigation plan provides direction and structure. Generally, investigators work through tasks as outlined in their plan:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Review and analyze complainant documentation</li>
                            <li>Inform the respondent they're under investigation (per agency requirements)</li>
                            <li>Interview witnesses in planned order</li>
                            <li>Collect physical and documentary evidence</li>
                            <li>Document findings systematically</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <h3>‚ö†Ô∏è Remaining Flexible</h3>
                    <div class="concept-card gold">
                        <p><strong>Expect the unexpected.</strong> Even with thorough planning, investigations rarely go exactly as planned:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Witnesses may become unavailable or uncooperative</li>
                            <li>You may need to interview witnesses out of original order</li>
                            <li>Documentation may not be available as expected</li>
                            <li>New information may require investigating additional leads</li>
                            <li>Parties may refuse to cooperate</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Key principle:</strong> Adapt your plan while maintaining focus on answering your six fundamental questions (Who, What, When, Where, Why, How).</p>
                    </div>

                    <h3>üéØ Management by Objectives (MBO)</h3>
                    <div class="concept-card burgundy">
                        <p>MBO is a goal-oriented approach that keeps investigations focused on results:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Objective-focused:</strong> All activities are designed to reach specific investigation goals</li>
                            <li><strong>Result-based:</strong> Investigations must produce findings that answer the fundamental questions</li>
                            <li><strong>Adaptable:</strong> Methods may change, but objectives remain constant</li>
                        </ul>
                        <div style="margin-top: 15px; padding: 15px; background: white; border-radius: 8px;">
                            <h4 style="color: #64092c; margin-bottom: 10px;">Application</h4>
                            <p>If a planned interview becomes impossible, identify alternative methods to obtain the same information. The objective (gathering that witness's account) remains; only the method changes.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h3>Sample Investigation Plan Framework</h3>
                    <p>Click to open each section to explore the components of a comprehensive investigation plan.</p>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(1)">
                            <span>1. Purpose and Scope</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-1">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-1">
                            <p><strong>Objective:</strong> Assess whether a licensed professional has violated statutes, regulations, or ethical standards governing their practice.</p>
                            <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Scope includes:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Alleged misconduct (e.g., fraud, negligence, unprofessional conduct)</li>
                                <li>Timeframe of alleged behavior</li>
                                <li>Jurisdictional relevance (licensee must be under agency authority)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(2)">
                            <span>2. Legal Authority</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-2">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-2">
                            <p><strong>Document your authority:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Statutory basis (e.g., State Professional Licensing Act)</li>
                                <li>Agency rules and regulations</li>
                                <li>Authority to compel testimony and issue subpoenas</li>
                                <li>Authority to access records</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(3)">
                            <span>3. Investigative Team</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-3">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-3">
                            <p><strong>Identify team members and roles:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Lead Investigator (compliance officer or enforcement agent)</li>
                                <li>Legal Counsel (advises on due process and statutory interpretation)</li>
                                <li>Subject Matter Expert (provides technical insight)</li>
                                <li>Support Staff (administrative and data analysts)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(4)">
                            <span>4. Preliminary Review</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-4">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-4">
                            <p><strong>Initial assessment:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Intake of complaint or referral</li>
                                <li>Screening for jurisdiction, credibility, and sufficiency</li>
                                <li>Decision to open formal investigation</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(5)">
                            <span>5. Investigation Strategy</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-5">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-5">
                            <p><strong>Evidence collection plan:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Licensee records (patient charts, billing, case files)</li>
                                <li>Public records (court filings, arrest records)</li>
                                <li>Witness interviews (patients, colleagues, employers)</li>
                                <li>Licensee interview (voluntary or compelled)</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Timeline:</strong> 30-90 days for initial findings, with extensions based on complexity.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(6)">
                            <span>6. Evidence Handling</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-6">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-6">
                            <p><strong>Proper evidence management:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Secure digital and physical storage</li>
                                <li>Chain of custody documentation</li>
                                <li>Redaction of sensitive third-party data (HIPAA compliance)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(7)">
                            <span>7. Legal and Ethical Safeguards</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-7">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-7">
                            <p><strong>Due process requirements:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Notice of investigation to licensee</li>
                                <li>Opportunity to respond or rebut allegations</li>
                                <li>Confidentiality of investigation until final disposition</li>
                                <li>Protection of complainant identity (when appropriate)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(8)">
                            <span>8. Reporting</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-8">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-8">
                            <p><strong>Draft investigative report with:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Factual findings</li>
                                <li>Legal analysis</li>
                                <li>Recommendations (dismissal, disciplinary hearing, settlement)</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p style="margin-top: 10px;">Internal review by legal and executive staff before submission to licensing board or administrative law judge.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(9)">
                            <span>9. Post-Investigation Actions</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-9">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-9">
                            <p><strong>Final steps:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Board vote on disciplinary action</li>
                                <li>Referral to law enforcement if criminal conduct suspected</li>
                                <li>Public notification (license status updates, press release)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(10)">
                            <span>10. Documentation and Recordkeeping</span>
                            <span class="accordion-arrow" id="arrow-10">‚ñ∫</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-content" id="content-10">
                            <p><strong>Maintain complete investigation file:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Original complaint</li>
                                <li>All correspondence</li>
                                <li>Evidence logs and chain of custody</li>
                                <li>Interview notes and recordings</li>
                                <li>Final investigation report</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p style="margin-top: 10px;">Retain per agency retention schedule. Investigation files may be needed years later for appeals or related proceedings.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 30px;">
                        <h4>üí° Execution Principle</h4>
                        <p>Plans guide your investigation, but judgment guides your decisions. When circumstances change, adapt your methods while staying focused on your objectives. Document all decisions and changes to your plan.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

