                    <h3>Final Thought</h3>
                    <div class="concept-card gray">
                        <p>Investigations are among the most sensitive and consequential activities regulatory agencies undertake. When someone files a complaint, they're trusting your agency to take it seriously and investigate thoroughly. When someone is the subject of an investigation, their livelihood and reputation are at stake.</p>

                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;">This responsibility requires both systematic rigor and sound judgment. The investigations plan provides a structured approach that ensures you ask the right questions, gather the right evidence, and respect legal boundaries. Your judgment provides the flexibility to adapt when circumstances change and the wisdom to balance public protection with fundamental fairness.</p>

                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;">Remember that investigations don't exist in isolation. They're part of a larger regulatory system designed to protect the public. A well-conducted investigation provides the evidence needed for informed decisions about disciplinary action, referral to law enforcement, or case closure. It creates a record that will withstand scrutiny months or years later when cases are reviewed or appealed.</p>

                        <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Your role as an investigator matters.</strong> The care you take in planning, the thoroughness of your evidence gathering, and your respect for both public protection and constitutional rights directly impact the quality of regulatory enforcement and public safety.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

